body:
Async JavaScript is where most bugs live. Race conditions, unhandled rejections, sequential fetches that should be parallel — these are the mistakes that slow down apps and frustrate users. Here are the patterns that fix them.

## 1. async/await Basics

The foundation. Always use async/await over raw Promises for readability:

```javascript
// Bad — callback hell
fetch('/api/user')
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(user => fetch(`/api/posts/${user.id}`))
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(posts => console.log(posts))
  .catch(err => console.error(err))

// Good — async/await
async function getUserPosts(userId) {
  try {
    const userRes = await fetch('/api/user')
    const user = await userRes.json()
    const postsRes = await fetch(`/api/posts/${user.id}`)
    return await postsRes.json()
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch posts:', err)
    throw err
  }
}
```

## 2. Promise.all — Parallel Fetches

The most common performance mistake: fetching things sequentially when they could be parallel.

```javascript
// Bad — sequential (slow)
const user = await fetchUser(id)
const posts = await fetchPosts(id)
const comments = await fetchComments(id)
// Total time: user + posts + comments

// Good — parallel (fast)
const [user, posts, comments] = await Promise.all([
  fetchUser(id),
  fetchPosts(id),
  fetchComments(id)
])
// Total time: max(user, posts, comments)
```

**Warning:** `Promise.all` fails fast — if any promise rejects, the whole thing rejects. Use `Promise.allSettled` if you want all results regardless of failures.

## 3. Promise.allSettled — Resilient Parallel Fetches

```javascript
const results = await Promise.allSettled([
  fetchUser(id),
  fetchPosts(id),
  fetchComments(id)
])

const [userResult, postsResult, commentsResult] = results

if (userResult.status === 'fulfilled') {
  console.log(userResult.value)
} else {
  console.error('User fetch failed:', userResult.reason)
}
```

## 4. Retry Logic

Network requests fail. Build retry logic into your fetch wrapper:

```javascript
async function fetchWithRetry(url, options = {}, retries = 3, delay = 1000) {
  for (let attempt = 0; attempt < retries; attempt++) {
    try {
      const res = await fetch(url, options)
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`)
      return await res.json()
    } catch (err) {
      if (attempt === retries - 1) throw err
      await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, delay * (attempt + 1)))
    }
  }
}
```

## 5. Concurrency Limiting

Don't fire 100 requests at once — rate limits and server load matter:

```javascript
async function processInBatches(items, batchSize, processor) {
  const results = []
  for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i += batchSize) {
    const batch = items.slice(i, i + batchSize)
    const batchResults = await Promise.all(batch.map(processor))
    results.push(...batchResults)
  }
  return results
}

// Process 100 items, 5 at a time
const results = await processInBatches(items, 5, async (item) => {
  return await processItem(item)
})
```

## 6. Timeout Wrapper

Don't let slow requests hang forever:

```javascript
function withTimeout(promise, ms) {
  const timeout = new Promise((_, reject) =>
    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`Timed out after ${ms}ms`)), ms)
  )
  return Promise.race([promise, timeout])
}

const data = await withTimeout(fetchData(), 5000)
```

## 7. Async Error Boundaries in React

```jsx
function useAsync(asyncFn, deps = []) {
  const [state, setState] = useState({ loading: true, data: null, error: null })

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false
    setState({ loading: true, data: null, error: null })

    asyncFn()
      .then(data => { if (!cancelled) setState({ loading: false, data, error: null }) })
      .catch(error => { if (!cancelled) setState({ loading: false, data: null, error }) })

    return () => { cancelled = true } // Cleanup prevents state updates after unmount
  }, deps)

  return state
}
```

## The Golden Rules

1. Always handle errors — unhandled rejections crash Node.js processes
2. Parallel > sequential when requests are independent
3. Add timeouts to every external request
4. Use `Promise.allSettled` when partial failure is acceptable
5. Cancel async operations on component unmount in React
